        {
          "title": "From Chatbots to Agents",
          "slug": "from-chatbots-to-agents",
          "order_index": 0,
          "content": "# From Chatbots to Agents\n\nA chatbot answers questions. An agent *does things*. This distinction \u2014 between generating a response and taking action in the world \u2014 is the defining shift in how we build AI systems today. Understanding what makes something an agent, rather than a sophisticated autocomplete, is the foundation for everything else in this course.\n\n## What Makes Something an \"Agent\"?\n\nA traditional chatbot receives a prompt and returns a single response. An **agent** receives a goal and pursues it through a loop of autonomous actions. The key differences:\n\n| Property | Chatbot | Agent |\n|----------|---------|-------|\n| Interaction | Single turn or multi-turn Q&A | Goal-driven, multi-step execution |\n| Tool use | None | Calls APIs, runs code, searches the web |\n| Decision-making | Stateless response generation | Plans, reasons, adapts |\n| Autonomy | User drives every step | Agent decides what to do next |\n\nAn agent doesn't just *say* it will book your flight \u2014 it searches for flights, compares options, fills in your details, and confirms the booking.\n\n## The Agent Loop\n\nAt the heart of every agent is a loop:\n\n1. **Observe** \u2014 perceive the current state (user input, tool results, environment)\n2. **Think** \u2014 reason about what to do next (often via an LLM)\n3. **Act** \u2014 execute an action (call a tool, send a message, update state)\n4. **Observe** \u2014 check the result, then loop back\n\nThis **observe \u2192 think \u2192 act** cycle repeats until the agent decides the goal is met or it should stop. A chatbot runs this loop exactly once. An agent runs it as many times as needed.\n\n## Key Properties of Agents\n\nClassical AI research (Russell & Norvig, Wooldridge & Jennings) identified four properties that define an agent:\n\n- **Autonomy** \u2014 operates without direct human intervention for each step\n- **Reactivity** \u2014 perceives its environment and responds to changes\n- **Proactivity** \u2014 takes initiative toward goals, doesn't just wait for instructions\n- **Social ability** \u2014 interacts with other agents or humans to accomplish tasks\n\nModern LLM-based agents exhibit all four: they autonomously decide which tools to call (autonomy), handle unexpected errors (reactivity), break down complex goals into sub-tasks (proactivity), and can collaborate with other agents or ask humans for clarification (social ability).\n\n## From Classical to Modern Agents\n\nThe idea of AI agents is not new. Classical AI explored rule-based agents, BDI (Belief-Desire-Intention) architectures, and reinforcement learning agents for decades. What changed is the **reasoning engine**: replacing hand-coded rules with a large language model gives agents general-purpose reasoning, natural language understanding, and the ability to handle open-ended tasks.\n\nThe modern LLM agent stack looks like: an LLM as the \"brain,\" a set of tools as the \"hands,\" memory as the \"notebook,\" and a planning strategy as the \"executive function.\"\n\n## Key Takeaways\n\n- Agents are defined by autonomous, goal-directed behavior \u2014 not just response generation\n- The agent loop (observe \u2192 think \u2192 act) is the core execution pattern\n- LLMs transformed agents from narrow, rule-based systems into general-purpose reasoners\n- Autonomy, reactivity, proactivity, and social ability are the four classical agent properties\n",
          "summary": "AI agents are autonomous, goal-directed systems that go beyond chatbot-style Q&A by reasoning, using tools, and executing multi-step plans in a continuous observe-think-act loop.",
          "concepts": [
            "agent loop",
            "autonomy",
            "reactivity",
            "proactivity",
            "goal-directed behavior",
            "LLM agents"
          ],
          "youtube_id": null,
          "video_title": null,
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
        },
        {
          "title": "Reasoning & Planning",
          "slug": "reasoning-and-planning",
          "order_index": 1,
          "content": "# Reasoning & Planning\n\nAn agent that can call tools but can't reason about *when* and *why* to call them is just a random tool invoker. Reasoning and planning are what separate a useful agent from a chaotic one. This lesson covers the techniques that give agents the ability to think before they act \u2014 and to fix their mistakes when things go wrong.\n\n## Chain-of-Thought as Internal Monologue\n\n**Chain-of-thought (CoT)** prompting asks the LLM to \"think step by step\" before producing an answer. For agents, this becomes an internal monologue \u2014 a scratchpad where the model reasons about the current situation, considers options, and decides on the next action.\n\nWithout CoT, an LLM might jump directly to a tool call that seems plausible but is wrong. With CoT, it first articulates *why* that tool call makes sense, catches logical errors, and produces more reliable action sequences.\n\n## The ReAct Pattern\n\n**ReAct** (Reason + Act), introduced by Yao et al. in 2022, is the foundational paradigm for agentic reasoning. It interleaves reasoning traces with actions in a structured loop:\n\n```\nThought: I need to find the current stock price of NVIDIA.\nAction: search(\"NVIDIA stock price today\")\nObservation: NVIDIA (NVDA) is trading at $142.50.\nThought: Now I have the price. The user also asked for the market cap.\nAction: search(\"NVIDIA market cap\")\nObservation: NVIDIA market cap is $3.5 trillion.\nThought: I have both pieces of information. I can answer now.\nAnswer: NVIDIA is trading at $142.50 with a market cap of $3.5T.\n```\n\nThe key insight: by making the model *write down its reasoning*, we get transparency, debuggability, and better decision-making.\n\n## Plan-and-Execute\n\nFor complex tasks, step-by-step reasoning isn't enough \u2014 the agent needs to create a plan upfront. The **plan-and-execute** pattern separates planning from execution:\n\n1. **Planner** \u2014 an LLM call that decomposes the goal into a numbered list of sub-tasks\n2. **Executor** \u2014 a separate agent (or the same LLM) that executes each sub-task\n3. **Re-planner** \u2014 after each step, optionally revise the remaining plan based on results\n\nThis is especially powerful for tasks with dependencies: \"Research competitors, then draft a comparison table, then write a summary email.\"\n\n## Tree of Thoughts\n\n**Tree of Thoughts (ToT)** extends chain-of-thought by exploring multiple reasoning paths simultaneously. Instead of committing to one chain, the agent branches at decision points, evaluates each branch, and prunes dead ends. Think of it as the difference between greedy search and beam search applied to reasoning.\n\nToT is computationally expensive (it requires multiple LLM calls per decision point) but excels at tasks where the first idea isn't always the best \u2014 puzzles, code generation, strategic planning.\n\n## Reflection and Self-Correction\n\nAgents make mistakes. **Reflection** is the practice of having the agent evaluate its own output and try again if it falls short:\n\n- **Reflexion** (Shinn et al., 2023) \u2014 the agent receives feedback on a failed attempt, writes a reflection about what went wrong, and uses that reflection to guide a better second attempt\n- **Self-consistency** \u2014 generate multiple solutions and pick the most common answer\n- **Critic patterns** \u2014 a second LLM call reviews the first call's output for errors\n\nReflection turns a single-shot agent into one that iteratively improves \u2014 a crucial capability for production systems.\n\n## Recommended Reading\n\n- [ReAct: Synergizing Reasoning and Acting in Language Models](https://arxiv.org/abs/2210.03629) \u2014 the original ReAct paper by Yao et al. (2022)\n- [LLM Powered Autonomous Agents](https://lilianweng.github.io/posts/2023-06-23-agent/) \u2014 Lilian Weng's comprehensive survey of agent architectures\n",
          "summary": "Reasoning and planning techniques \u2014 including chain-of-thought, ReAct, plan-and-execute, and reflection \u2014 enable agents to think before they act and self-correct when they make mistakes.",
          "concepts": [
            "chain-of-thought",
            "ReAct",
            "plan-and-execute",
            "tree of thoughts",
            "reflection",
            "self-correction"
          ],
          "youtube_id": null,
          "video_title": null,
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
        }
