      "title": "Tool Use & Function Calling",
      "order_index": 1,
      "lessons": [
        {
          "title": "Function Calling & APIs",
          "slug": "function-calling-apis",
          "order_index": 0,
          "content": "# Function Calling & APIs\n\nLanguage models generate text. But text alone can't check the weather, query a database, or send an email. **Function calling** bridges this gap \u2014 it lets an LLM declare that it wants to invoke a specific function with specific arguments, turning a language model into a general-purpose controller for external systems.\n\n## The Paradigm Shift\n\nBefore function calling, integrating LLMs with tools required fragile prompt engineering: \"Output your answer as JSON with a 'tool' field and an 'args' field.\" The model would frequently produce malformed output, forget fields, or hallucinate tool names.\n\nModern LLM APIs (OpenAI, Anthropic, Google) support **native function calling**: the model is trained to output structured tool invocations that are guaranteed to match a declared schema. This is not prompt engineering \u2014 it's a first-class capability of the model.\n\n## Tool Schemas\n\nTools are defined using **JSON Schema** \u2014 a standard format that describes function names, parameters, types, and descriptions:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"type\": \"function\",\n  \"function\": {\n    \"name\": \"get_weather\",\n    \"description\": \"Get current weather for a city\",\n    \"parameters\": {\n      \"type\": \"object\",\n      \"properties\": {\n        \"city\": { \"type\": \"string\", \"description\": \"City name\" },\n        \"units\": { \"type\": \"string\", \"enum\": [\"celsius\", \"fahrenheit\"] }\n      },\n      \"required\": [\"city\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nThe quality of your tool descriptions directly impacts how well the model uses them. Vague descriptions lead to incorrect tool calls.\n\n## The Tool-Use Loop\n\nFunction calling follows a precise loop:\n\n1. **User sends a message** \u2014 \"What's the weather in Tokyo?\"\n2. **LLM returns a tool call** \u2014 `get_weather({\"city\": \"Tokyo\", \"units\": \"celsius\"})`\n3. **Your code executes the function** and returns the result to the LLM\n4. **LLM generates a natural language response** using the tool result\n\nThis loop can repeat: the LLM might call multiple tools sequentially, using the output of one tool as input to the next.\n\n## Types of Tools\n\nAgents commonly use several categories of tools:\n\n| Category | Examples | Use Cases |\n|----------|----------|-----------|\n| **APIs** | REST endpoints, GraphQL | Weather, stock prices, CRM data |\n| **Databases** | SQL queries, vector search | Structured data retrieval |\n| **Search** | Web search, document search | Real-time information, RAG |\n| **Computation** | Calculators, code execution | Math, data analysis |\n| **Communication** | Email, Slack, notifications | User-facing actions |\n\n## Parallel Tool Calling\n\nModern APIs support **parallel tool calling** \u2014 the model can request multiple tool invocations in a single response. If a user asks \"What's the weather in Tokyo and New York?\", the model returns two tool calls simultaneously rather than sequentially, reducing latency.\n\n## Model Context Protocol (MCP)\n\nEvery LLM provider has its own function calling format. Every tool has its own integration pattern. **Model Context Protocol (MCP)** is an open standard (introduced by Anthropic, now widely adopted) that standardizes how agents discover, connect to, and use tools and data sources.\n\nMCP defines three primitives:\n\n- **Tools** \u2014 functions the agent can call (same concept as function calling, but with a standard discovery mechanism)\n- **Resources** \u2014 data the agent can read (files, database records, API responses)\n- **Prompts** \u2014 reusable prompt templates that tools can expose\n\nThe key idea: instead of hardcoding tool integrations, an agent connects to **MCP servers** that advertise their capabilities. The agent discovers available tools at runtime, reads their schemas, and calls them through a uniform protocol \u2014 whether the tool is a local file system, a remote API, a database, or a third-party service.\n\n```\nAgent \u2500\u2500MCP\u2500\u2500\u25ba Local File Server    (read/write files)\n       \u2500\u2500MCP\u2500\u2500\u25ba Database Server      (query, insert)\n       \u2500\u2500MCP\u2500\u2500\u25ba Web Search Server    (search the web)\n       \u2500\u2500MCP\u2500\u2500\u25ba Custom Tool Server   (domain-specific tools)\n```\n\nMCP matters because it turns tool integration from a bespoke engineering problem into a plug-and-play ecosystem \u2014 much like HTTP standardized web communication.\n\n## Error Handling\n\nTools fail. APIs time out, queries return empty results, permissions get denied. Robust agents need:\n\n- **Retry logic** with exponential backoff for transient failures\n- **Fallback tools** \u2014 if web search fails, try a different search provider\n- **Graceful degradation** \u2014 inform the user when a tool is unavailable rather than crashing\n- **Validation** \u2014 check tool arguments before execution to catch obvious errors\n\n## Recommended Reading\n\n- [OpenAI Function Calling Guide](https://platform.openai.com/docs/guides/function-calling) \u2014 the canonical reference for tool-use APIs\n",
          "summary": "Function calling lets LLMs invoke external tools via structured schemas, turning language models into controllers for APIs, databases, search engines, and other external systems.",
          "concepts": [
            "function calling",
            "tool schemas",
            "JSON Schema",
            "tool-use loop",
            "parallel tool calling",
            "error handling",
            "Model Context Protocol"
          ],
          "youtube_id": null,
          "video_title": null,
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
        },
        {
          "title": "Code Execution & Retrieval Tools",
          "slug": "code-execution-retrieval",
          "order_index": 1,
          "content": "# Code Execution & Retrieval Tools\n\nFunction calling gives agents access to pre-defined tools. But some of the most powerful agent capabilities come from two special tool categories: **code execution** (agents that write and run their own programs) and **retrieval** (agents that search through knowledge bases to ground their responses in facts).\n\n## The Code Interpreter Pattern\n\nInstead of calling a fixed set of functions, a code interpreter agent can **write arbitrary code** to solve novel problems. Need to parse a CSV, generate a chart, solve a differential equation, or transform data? The agent writes a Python script, executes it, and uses the output.\n\nThe typical flow:\n\n1. Agent receives a task \u2014 \"Analyze this sales data and find the top 3 regions\"\n2. Agent writes Python code \u2014 pandas loading, groupby, sorting\n3. Code runs in a **sandboxed environment** and returns stdout/stderr\n4. Agent interprets the output and responds to the user\n\nThis pattern is incredibly flexible because it turns the agent into a programmer with access to the entire Python ecosystem.\n\n## Sandboxed Execution\n\nRunning arbitrary LLM-generated code is dangerous without isolation. **Sandboxed execution environments** provide safety:\n\n- **E2B** \u2014 cloud-hosted sandboxes with pre-installed packages, filesystem access, and network isolation\n- **Docker containers** \u2014 lightweight isolation with controlled resource limits\n- **Firecracker microVMs** \u2014 full VM isolation (used by AWS Lambda)\n\nKey constraints for safe sandboxing:\n- No network access (or restricted allowlists)\n- CPU/memory/time limits to prevent runaway processes\n- No access to host filesystem or secrets\n- Ephemeral \u2014 destroyed after execution\n\n## RAG as a Tool\n\n**Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG)** is often implemented as a pipeline, but in agentic systems it becomes a tool the agent can choose to call. The agent decides *when* retrieval is necessary rather than always retrieving.\n\nAs a tool, RAG typically looks like:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"name\": \"search_knowledge_base\",\n  \"description\": \"Search internal documents for relevant information\",\n  \"parameters\": {\n    \"query\": { \"type\": \"string\" },\n    \"top_k\": { \"type\": \"integer\", \"default\": 5 }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nThe agent formulates the search query (often reformulating the user's question for better retrieval), receives chunks of relevant text, and synthesizes an answer grounded in those sources.\n\n## Web Browsing and Scraping\n\nWeb browsing tools let agents access live information beyond their training data. Implementations range from simple (fetch a URL and extract text) to complex (headless browser with navigation, clicking, and form-filling). Web browsing is essential for tasks like research, fact-checking, and monitoring.\n\n## Structured Data & SQL Generation\n\nFor agents working with databases, **text-to-SQL** is a critical capability. The agent translates natural language questions into SQL queries, executes them against a database, and interprets the results. This requires the agent to understand the database schema \u2014 typically provided as a tool description or retrieved from metadata tables.\n\n## When to Use Which Tool\n\n| Task | Best Tool |\n|------|-----------|\n| Data analysis, charts | Code interpreter |\n| Factual questions about documents | RAG / knowledge base search |\n| Real-time information | Web search / browsing |\n| Database queries | SQL generation |\n| Math, calculations | Code interpreter or calculator |\n| File manipulation | Code interpreter |\n\nThe key insight: a well-designed agent doesn't just have tools \u2014 it knows *when* each tool is the right choice.\n",
          "summary": "Code execution and retrieval tools expand agent capabilities beyond pre-defined functions \u2014 enabling agents to write and run code, search knowledge bases, browse the web, and query databases.",
          "concepts": [
            "code interpreter",
            "sandboxed execution",
            "retrieval-augmented generation",
            "text-to-SQL",
            "web browsing",
            "E2B"
          ],
          "youtube_id": null,
          "video_title": null,
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
        }
