        {
          "title": "Conversation Memory & Context",
          "slug": "conversation-memory-context",
          "order_index": 0,
          "content": "# Conversation Memory & Context\n\nEvery LLM has a finite **context window** \u2014 the maximum number of tokens it can process in a single call. For GPT-4o that's 128K tokens; for Claude, 200K. This sounds like a lot, but agent conversations with tool results, system prompts, and conversation history can fill it up fast. Managing what goes into that window is one of the most practical challenges in building agents.\n\n## Short-Term Memory: Conversation History\n\nThe simplest form of agent memory is the full conversation history \u2014 every user message, assistant response, and tool call/result appended to the messages array. This gives the agent perfect recall of everything that happened in the current session.\n\nThe problem: long conversations eventually exceed the context window. A 50-turn conversation with tool results can easily reach 50K+ tokens.\n\n## Summarization Strategies\n\nWhen conversations grow too long, **summarization** compresses older messages into a shorter representation:\n\n- **Rolling summary** \u2014 periodically summarize the oldest N messages into a single summary message, then drop the originals\n- **Hierarchical summarization** \u2014 summarize summaries for very long conversations\n- **Key-point extraction** \u2014 extract only decisions, facts, and action items from older turns\n\n```\nSystem: Here is a summary of the conversation so far:\n- User is building a Python web scraper for news articles\n- We chose BeautifulSoup over Scrapy for simplicity\n- The scraper handles pagination and saves to CSV\n- Current issue: some articles have JavaScript-rendered content\n```\n\nThe trade-off is clear: summarization loses detail. The agent may forget a specific preference the user mentioned 30 turns ago.\n\n## Sliding Window Approaches\n\nA **sliding window** keeps only the most recent N messages (or N tokens) in context. Older messages are dropped entirely. This is simple and predictable but means the agent has no memory of early conversation.\n\nA hybrid approach keeps:\n- The **system prompt** (always)\n- A **summary** of older conversation\n- The **last K messages** in full\n\nThis gives the agent both long-term context (via summary) and short-term precision (via recent messages).\n\n## Message Trimming and Prioritization\n\nNot all messages are equally important. Smart trimming strategies prioritize:\n\n- **User messages over assistant messages** \u2014 what the user asked matters more than how the agent responded\n- **Tool results with data over empty results** \u2014 failed tool calls can often be dropped\n- **Decision points over chit-chat** \u2014 keep messages where the user made a choice\n- **Recent messages over old ones** \u2014 recency bias is usually correct for agents\n\n## System Prompt as Persistent Memory\n\nThe **system prompt** is the one piece of context that's always present. Agents often use it as persistent memory by dynamically updating it with key information:\n\n- User preferences discovered during conversation\n- Project context and constraints\n- Running list of completed tasks\n- Current plan and next steps\n\nSome frameworks automatically inject retrieved context (user profile, relevant docs) into the system prompt before each LLM call.\n\n## Key Takeaways\n\n- Context window management is a core engineering challenge for agents\n- Summarization trades detail for capacity \u2014 use it for older context\n- Sliding window + summary is the most practical default strategy\n- The system prompt serves as an always-present persistent memory slot\n",
          "summary": "Managing conversation memory within the LLM's finite context window requires strategies like summarization, sliding windows, and message prioritization to balance recall with capacity.",
          "concepts": [
            "context window",
            "conversation history",
            "summarization",
            "sliding window",
            "message trimming",
            "system prompt"
          ],
          "youtube_id": null,
          "video_title": null,
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
        },
        {
          "title": "Long-Term Memory & Knowledge",
          "slug": "long-term-memory-knowledge",
          "order_index": 1,
          "content": "# Long-Term Memory & Knowledge\n\nConversation memory disappears when the session ends. For agents that interact with users over days, weeks, or months, **long-term memory** \u2014 persistent state that survives across sessions \u2014 is essential. This lesson covers how agents remember things permanently and retrieve the right memories at the right time.\n\n## Why Long-Term Memory Matters\n\nConsider a personal assistant agent. Without long-term memory, every conversation starts from scratch: \"What's your name? What project are you working on? What programming language do you prefer?\" With it, the agent remembers your preferences, past decisions, and ongoing projects \u2014 it becomes genuinely useful over time.\n\n## Types of Long-Term Memory\n\nCognitive science distinguishes several types of memory, and agent architectures borrow this taxonomy:\n\n| Memory Type | What It Stores | Agent Example |\n|-------------|---------------|---------------|\n| **Episodic** | Specific past experiences | \"Last Tuesday, the user asked me to refactor the auth module\" |\n| **Semantic** | General facts and knowledge | \"The user prefers Python over JavaScript\" |\n| **Procedural** | How to do things | \"When deploying, always run tests first\" |\n\n## Vector Stores as Memory\n\nThe dominant implementation pattern uses **vector databases** (Pinecone, Weaviate, Chroma, pgvector) to store and retrieve memories:\n\n1. **Store** \u2014 when something worth remembering happens, embed it as a vector and save it with metadata (timestamp, topic, importance)\n2. **Retrieve** \u2014 before each LLM call, search the vector store for memories relevant to the current query\n3. **Inject** \u2014 add retrieved memories to the context (system prompt or user message)\n\nThe embedding model's quality directly determines retrieval quality. Memories that are semantically similar to the current conversation get surfaced; unrelated memories stay dormant.\n\n## Memory Retrieval: What to Remember, When to Forget\n\nNot everything should be remembered forever. Good memory systems implement:\n\n- **Relevance scoring** \u2014 retrieve only memories above a similarity threshold\n- **Recency weighting** \u2014 boost recent memories over old ones\n- **Importance scoring** \u2014 some memories (user preferences, key decisions) matter more than others (casual comments)\n- **Decay** \u2014 gradually reduce the weight of old, unretrieved memories\n- **Consolidation** \u2014 merge similar memories into a single, refined memory\n\n## Knowledge Graphs\n\n**Knowledge graphs** store structured relationships between entities: (User, prefers, Python), (Project-X, uses, PostgreSQL), (Meeting, scheduled_for, Friday). They complement vector stores by enabling relationship-based queries: \"What tools does Project X use?\" rather than just similarity search.\n\nSome agent frameworks automatically extract entities and relationships from conversations to build a knowledge graph incrementally.\n\n## Memory-Focused Frameworks\n\nSeveral frameworks specialize in agent memory:\n\n- **Mem0** \u2014 automatic memory extraction and retrieval; identifies \"memory-worthy\" moments in conversations and stores them without explicit instructions\n- **Zep** \u2014 long-term memory with built-in summarization, entity extraction, and temporal awareness\n- **LangGraph's checkpointing** \u2014 persists full agent state (messages, tool results, internal variables) across sessions\n\n## User Profiles and Personalization\n\nThe most impactful use of long-term memory is **personalization**. By maintaining a user profile that evolves over time, agents can:\n\n- Adapt communication style (technical vs. casual)\n- Remember preferences and constraints\n- Anticipate needs based on past behavior\n- Avoid repeating information the user already knows\n\n## Recommended Reading\n\n- [Building Effective Agents](https://www.anthropic.com/engineering/building-effective-agents) \u2014 Anthropic's practical guide to agent architectures, including memory patterns\n",
          "summary": "Long-term memory systems use vector stores, knowledge graphs, and memory frameworks to give agents persistent recall across sessions \u2014 enabling personalization and continuous context.",
          "concepts": [
            "long-term memory",
            "vector stores",
            "episodic memory",
            "semantic memory",
            "knowledge graphs",
            "Mem0",
            "personalization"
          ],
          "youtube_id": null,
          "video_title": null,
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
        }
