    {
      "title": "Multi-Agent Systems",
      "order_index": 3,
      "lessons": [
        {
          "title": "Multi-Agent Architectures",
          "slug": "multi-agent-architectures",
          "order_index": 0,
          "content": "# Multi-Agent Architectures\n\nA single agent can do a lot, but complex tasks often benefit from **division of labor**. Just as a software team has specialized roles (frontend, backend, QA), multi-agent systems assign different agents to different subtasks. This lesson explores the architectural patterns for organizing multiple agents into effective teams.\n\n## Why Multiple Agents?\n\nA single agent with dozens of tools and a massive system prompt can become unwieldy. Multi-agent architectures solve several problems:\n\n- **Specialization** \u2014 each agent has a focused role with fewer tools and a targeted system prompt, improving reliability\n- **Modularity** \u2014 agents can be developed, tested, and updated independently\n- **Parallelism** \u2014 independent subtasks can run concurrently across agents\n- **Separation of concerns** \u2014 the \"researcher\" agent doesn't need to know how to write code, and the \"coder\" agent doesn't need web search\n\n## The Supervisor Pattern\n\nThe most common architecture places a **supervisor** (or orchestrator) agent in charge:\n\n1. The supervisor receives the user's goal\n2. It decides which worker agent to delegate to\n3. The worker executes and returns results\n4. The supervisor decides the next step \u2014 delegate again, ask the user, or finalize\n\nThe supervisor typically has no tools of its own \u2014 its \"tool\" is delegating to other agents. It reasons about task decomposition and sequencing.\n\n## Hierarchical Teams\n\n**Hierarchical architectures** extend the supervisor pattern with multiple levels. A top-level supervisor delegates to mid-level supervisors, who delegate to specialized workers:\n\n```\n          CEO Agent\n          /       \\\n   Research Lead    Engineering Lead\n    /      \\          /        \\\n Searcher  Analyst   Coder    Tester\n```\n\nThis mirrors how large organizations work: strategic decisions at the top, tactical execution at the bottom. It scales to complex tasks that a flat structure can't handle.\n\n## Peer-to-Peer Collaboration\n\nIn **peer-to-peer** architectures, agents communicate directly without a central supervisor. Each agent knows about its peers and can send messages or delegate subtasks laterally. This is more flexible but harder to debug \u2014 there's no single point of control.\n\nPeer-to-peer works well when agents have equal authority and the task requires back-and-forth collaboration, like a brainstorming session between a writer and an editor.\n\n## Debate and Consensus\n\nSome multi-agent systems use **debate** as a mechanism for improving output quality:\n\n1. Multiple agents independently propose solutions\n2. Agents critique each other's proposals\n3. Through rounds of debate, they converge on a consensus answer\n\nResearch shows that LLM debate can improve accuracy on reasoning tasks \u2014 agents catch each other's mistakes. The debate pattern is particularly useful for high-stakes decisions where a single agent's reasoning might be flawed.\n\n## Common Agent Roles\n\nRecurring role patterns in multi-agent teams:\n\n| Role | Responsibility |\n|------|---------------|\n| **Researcher** | Search, gather information, synthesize findings |\n| **Writer** | Draft content, reports, documentation |\n| **Critic** | Review, find errors, suggest improvements |\n| **Coder** | Write and debug code |\n| **Planner** | Decompose tasks, create execution plans |\n| **Executor** | Run tools, execute plans step by step |\n\nThe power of multi-agent systems comes from composing these roles into teams tailored to specific workflows.\n\n## Key Takeaways\n\n- Multi-agent systems trade single-agent simplicity for specialization and modularity\n- The supervisor pattern is the most common and easiest to reason about\n- Hierarchical teams scale to complex, multi-domain tasks\n- Debate and consensus patterns improve reliability through agent-to-agent critique\n",
          "summary": "Multi-agent architectures organize specialized agents into teams using patterns like supervisor, hierarchical, and peer-to-peer \u2014 enabling division of labor and parallel execution for complex tasks.",
          "concepts": [
            "multi-agent systems",
            "supervisor pattern",
            "hierarchical teams",
            "peer-to-peer",
            "agent roles",
            "debate and consensus"
          ],
          "youtube_id": null,
          "video_title": null,
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
        },
        {
          "title": "Agent Communication & Coordination",
          "slug": "agent-communication-coordination",
          "order_index": 1,
          "content": "# Agent Communication & Coordination\n\nHaving multiple agents is only useful if they can communicate effectively. This lesson covers how agents pass messages, share state, hand off control, and involve humans \u2014 the coordination layer that makes multi-agent systems work in practice.\n\n## Message Passing\n\nThe simplest coordination mechanism is **message passing**: one agent sends a message to another and waits for a response. Messages are typically structured as natural language (easy for LLMs to process) with optional metadata (sender, priority, task ID).\n\nIn practice, message passing often follows the tool-call pattern: the supervisor \"calls\" a worker agent the same way it would call a tool, passing a task description and receiving a result.\n\n## Shared State and Blackboard Patterns\n\nInstead of passing messages directly, agents can coordinate through **shared state** \u2014 a common data structure that all agents can read and write:\n\n- **Blackboard pattern** \u2014 a shared workspace where agents post partial results. Each agent monitors the blackboard and contributes when it has relevant expertise. A research agent posts findings; an analysis agent reads them and posts insights; a writer agent reads insights and drafts a report.\n- **Shared memory** \u2014 a key-value store or document that agents update collaboratively\n- **State graph** \u2014 frameworks like LangGraph represent agent state as a typed dictionary that flows through a graph of agent nodes\n\nThe blackboard pattern is powerful for loosely coupled agents that don't need to know about each other \u2014 they only need to know about the shared workspace.\n\n## Handoffs\n\n**Handoffs** transfer control from one agent to another, along with relevant context. Unlike message passing (where the sender waits for a reply), a handoff is a one-way transfer \u2014 the receiving agent takes over the conversation.\n\nHandoff design considerations:\n\n- **What context to pass** \u2014 full conversation history, a summary, or only the relevant subset?\n- **When to hand off** \u2014 rule-based triggers (\"if the user asks about billing, hand off to the billing agent\") or LLM-decided\n- **Return path** \u2014 does the receiving agent hand back, or does it own the conversation from here?\n\nOpenAI's Agents SDK makes handoffs a first-class concept: agents declare which other agents they can hand off to, and the framework handles context transfer.\n\n## Human-in-the-Loop\n\nNot everything should be fully autonomous. **Human-in-the-loop (HITL)** patterns involve a human at critical decision points:\n\n- **Approval gates** \u2014 the agent pauses and asks for human approval before executing high-stakes actions (sending emails, making purchases, deploying code)\n- **Clarification requests** \u2014 when the agent is uncertain, it asks the human rather than guessing\n- **Escalation** \u2014 when the agent detects it's stuck or out of its depth, it escalates to a human operator\n- **Review and correction** \u2014 the agent drafts output for human review before finalizing\n\nThe key principle: **automate the routine, escalate the exceptional**. Agents should handle 90% of cases autonomously and involve humans for the remaining 10% that require judgment.\n\n## Conflict Resolution\n\nWhen agents disagree \u2014 different researchers return contradictory information, or a coder and a reviewer clash on implementation \u2014 the system needs a resolution strategy:\n\n- **Supervisor decides** \u2014 the orchestrator agent makes the final call\n- **Voting** \u2014 majority wins across multiple agents\n- **Confidence-weighted** \u2014 the agent with higher confidence in its answer wins\n- **Human arbitration** \u2014 escalate unresolvable conflicts to a human\n\n## Scaling Agent Teams\n\nAs agent teams grow, coordination overhead increases. Practical strategies for scaling:\n\n- **Limit communication channels** \u2014 not every agent needs to talk to every other agent\n- **Hierarchical delegation** \u2014 use layers of supervisors to reduce the span of control\n- **Async execution** \u2014 let agents work in parallel and synchronize at checkpoints\n- **Stateless workers** \u2014 design worker agents to be stateless and interchangeable for easier scaling\n\n## Key Takeaways\n\n- Message passing and shared state are the two fundamental coordination mechanisms\n- Handoffs transfer full control between agents; design the context transfer carefully\n- Human-in-the-loop is essential for high-stakes actions \u2014 automate the routine, escalate the exceptional\n- Conflict resolution and scaling strategies become critical as agent teams grow\n",
          "summary": "Agent coordination relies on message passing, shared state, and handoffs \u2014 with human-in-the-loop patterns ensuring oversight for high-stakes decisions and conflict resolution when agents disagree.",
          "concepts": [
            "message passing",
            "shared state",
            "blackboard pattern",
            "handoffs",
            "human-in-the-loop",
            "conflict resolution",
            "scaling"
          ],
          "youtube_id": null,
          "video_title": null,
          "vimeo_url": null,
          "transcript": null
        }
      ]
